column1942: "Title":"CSV files for download - What are CSV files?"
column1946: "Content":"<h2><a name=\"what-are-csvs\"><\/a>What are CSV files?<\/h2><p>CSV files are text files with information separated by commas
column1947: &nbsp;saved with the extension .csv.&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">They allow large amounts of detailed data to be transferred \u2018machine-to-machine\u2019
column1948: with little or no reformatting by the user.<\/span><\/p><p>You can open a CSV file with any spreadsheet
column1953: or Python.&nbsp;<\/p><p>CSV files may open in Excel&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">by default<\/span><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">
column1954: but they are not designed as Excel files. If CSV files are opened in Excel
column1955: certain information (eg codes with leading zeros) could be missing. Ideally
column1956: they should be imported into a database designed to preserve the CSV format.<\/span><\/p>"}

What are CSV files?

CSV files are text files with information separated by commas
column191: saved with the extension .csv. <span style="font-size: 1rem;">They allow large amounts of detailed data to be transferred machine-to-machine
column192:
with little or no reformatting by the user.

You can open a CSV file with any spreadsheet
column197:
or Python. 

CSV files may open in Excel by default
column198: but they are not designed as Excel files. If CSV files are opened in Excel
column199: certain information (eg codes with leading zeros) could be missing. Ideally
column200:
they should be imported into a database designed to preserve the CSV format.

Find variable names in Infoshare

Because a CSV file may contain multiple tables from Infoshare
column201: some variable headings have generic labels.

column1: An example of a CSV file (opened in Excel) with generic variable names.
You can find the names of these variables in Infoshare.
